{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XdEtKU5ezuPLieMGbapqP1","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Cloche System Design\n     2→\n     3→## Overview\n     4→\n     5→Cloche is a system for grow-coding high quality applications. It provides containerized\n     6→environments for coding agents to operate in isolation, a workflow DSL for linking\n     7→agentic and script-driven tasks, validated code pipelines, and self-evolving tooling.\n     8→\n     9→This document describes the architecture for the MVP (v0.1).\n    10→\n    11→## System Components\n    12→\n    13→Cloche is a Go monorepo producing three binaries:\n    14→\n    15→```\n    16→cmd/\n    17→  cloche/         # CLI client (short-lived)\n    18→  cloched/        # Daemon/orchestrator (long-running)\n    19→  cloche-agent/   # In-container entrypoint (autonomous)\n    20→```\n    21→\n    22→### cloche (CLI)\n    23→\n    24→Short-lived process. Talks to `cloched` over gRPC (Unix socket locally, TCP remotely).\n    25→\n    26→Subcommands:\n    27→- `run <workflow>` — Launch a new workflow run\n    28→- `resume <run-id> [step]` — Resume a failed run from a specific step (or first failed step)\n    29→- `status [run-id]` — Check run status\n    30→- `logs <run-id>` — Stream logs from a running workflow (bidirectional gRPC stream)\n    31→- `stop <run-id>` — Cancel a running workflow (signals container with SIGTERM)\n    32→\n    33→Accepts prompt files or stdin input for user commands.\n    34→\n    35→### cloched (Daemon)\n    36→\n    37→Long-running process. Responsibilities:\n    38→- Launch and manage Docker containers for workflow runs\n    39→- Listen to status streams from running agents\n    40→- Record captures (step inputs, outputs, results, logs)\n    41→- Expose gRPC API for the CLI\n    42→- Persist state via pluggable storage (SQLite initially)\n    43→\n    44→The daemon does NOT interpret workflow logic. It knows \"container X is running workflow Y\"\n    45→and collects status. The agent is self-directing.\n    46→\n    47→### cloche-agent (In-Container Runtime)\n    48→\n    49→Autonomous process running inside the Docker container. Responsibilities:\n    50→- Parse the workflow DSL (workflow files live in the codebase)\n    51→- Walk the workflow graph, executing steps and following results\n    52→- Invoke coding agents (Claude Code, custom commands) and scripts\n    53→- Stream structured status events back to `cloched`\n    54→- Run to completion (`done` or `abort`) without human intervention\n    55→\n    56→The agent is told which workflow to execute at launch. It handles everything else.\n    57→\n    58→## Communication\n    59→\n    60→### CLI <-> Daemon: gRPC\n    61→\n    62→- Protobuf contracts define the API (the API is the spec)\n    63→- Bidirectional streaming for `logs` (tail container output in real-time)\n    64→- Unix socket for local communication, TCP for remote\n    65→\n    66→### Agent <-> Daemon: Structured JSON over stdout\n    67→\n    68→- The agent writes JSON-lines to stdout with status updates\n    69→- `cloched` attaches to the container's stdout stream via Docker API\n    70→- Messages include: step started, step completed (with result name), logs, errors\n    71→- Kill/cancel: daemon sends SIGTERM to container, agent handles graceful shutdown\n    72→\n    73→## Workflow DSL\n    74→\n    75→### Vocabulary\n    76→\n    77→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    78→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    79→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    80→| step     | A unit of work (type: `agent` or `script`)                         |\n    81→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    82→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step                              |\n    83→| done     | Built-in terminal step indicating successful completion            |\n    84→| abort    | Built-in terminal step indicating failure (reports error and exits)|\n    85→\n    86→### Syntax\n    87→\n    88→```\n    89→workflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    90→  step code {\n    91→    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n    92→    container {\n    93→      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    94→      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"internal-docs.company.com\"]\n    95→    }\n    96→    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    97→  }\n    98→\n    99→  step check {\n   100→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n   101→    results = [pass, fail]\n   102→  }\n   103→\n   104→  step review {\n   105→    prompt = file(\"prompts/review.md\")\n   106→    input = step.code.output\n   107→    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n   108→  }\n   109→\n   110→  code:success -> check\n   111→  code:fail -> abort\n   112→  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n   113→\n   114→  check:pass -> review\n   115→  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n   116→\n   117→  review:approved -> done\n   118→  review:changes_requested -> code\n   119→}\n   120→```\n   121→\n   122→### Key Properties\n   123→\n   124→- Step type is inferred from content: `prompt` field → agent step, `run` field → script step.\n   125→- Steps declare which results they can emit. The step decides at runtime which result to report.\n   126→- Wiring is separate from step definitions. This enables runtime injection of new steps\n   127→  (the self-evolution feature) — insert a new check between existing steps by rewiring,\n   128→  without modifying either step.\n   129→- `file()` loads external content (prompt files, scripts).\n   130→- Step inputs can reference other step outputs (`step.code.output`).\n   131→- The graph engine validates at parse time: all declared results are wired, no orphan steps,\n   132→  entry point exists.\n   133→\n   134→## Hexagonal Architecture\n   135→\n   136→The core domain is independent of Docker, gRPC, SQLite, or any other infrastructure.\n   137→\n   138→### Domain\n   139→\n   140→```\n   141→internal/domain/\n   142→  workflow.go    # Workflow, Step, Result, Graph types\n   143→  run.go         # Run, RunState, StepExecution types\n   144→  capture.go     # CapturedInput, CapturedOutput for replay\n   145→```\n   146→\n   147→### Ports (interfaces)\n   148→\n   149→```\n   150→internal/ports/\n   151→  store.go       # RunStore, WorkflowStore, CaptureStore\n   152→  container.go   # ContainerRuntime (start, stop, attach, logs)\n   153→  agent.go       # AgentAdapter (how to invoke an agent)\n   154→  notifier.go    # StatusNotifier (how to report progress)\n   155→```\n   156→\n   157→### Adapters (implementations)\n   158→\n   159→```\n   160→internal/adapters/\n   161→  docker/        # ContainerRuntime via Docker API\n   162→  sqlite/        # Store implementations via SQLite\n   163→  grpc/          # gRPC server (daemon) and client (CLI)\n   164→  agents/\n   165→    claudecode/  # AgentAdapter for Claude Code\n   166→    generic/     # AgentAdapter for arbitrary commands\n   167→```\n   168→\n   169→### Key Interfaces\n   170→\n   171→- **ContainerRuntime** — Start/stop containers, attach to stdout, copy files in/out.\n   172→  Docker today, Podman or Firecracker later.\n   173→- **RunStore** — Persist run state (active step, reported results, timestamps).\n   174→- **CaptureStore** — Store step inputs/outputs for replay. Git refs serve as pointers\n   175→  to file states; metadata lives in the store.\n   176→- **AgentAdapter** — Translates between Cloche's step protocol and a specific agent's\n   177→  interface. Claude Code adapter knows how to invoke `claude` CLI. Generic adapter runs\n   178→  any command.\n   179→- **StatusNotifier** — How the agent reports progress. Stdout JSON-lines initially.\n   180→\n   181→## Container Model\n   182→\n   183→### One Container Per Workflow Run\n   184→\n   185→A container is spun up for a workflow run. All steps execute inside the same container.\n   186→File state accumulates naturally across steps (agent modifies code, then test script\n   187→runs against those modifications).\n   188→\n   189→### Lifecycle\n   190→\n   191→1. `cloched` pulls/builds the container image\n   192→2. Copies project files into the container at `/workspace`\n   193→3. Starts the container with `cloche-agent` as entrypoint, passing the workflow name\n   194→4. `cloche-agent` parses the workflow, walks the graph, executes steps\n   195→5. Agent streams status events to `cloched` via stdout\n   196→6. At step boundaries, modified files are pushed to the host via git (agent-specific branch)\n   197→7. On completion (`done`/`abort`), container is stopped\n   198→\n   199→### File Extraction via Git\n   200→\n   201→The container's git remote is configured to push to the host repository. Each run pushes\n   202→to a unique branch (e.g. `cloche/run-<id>/step-<name>`). This provides:\n   203→- Full git history of what the agent did\n   204→- Trivial diffs between input and output states\n   205→- Clean branch-per-step organization\n   206→- No bind mounts (maintains isolation)\n   207→\n   208→### Security Boundaries\n   209→\n   210→1. **Filesystem** — No access beyond `/workspace`. Copy-in at start, git push for extraction.\n   211→2. **Network** — `--network none` by default. If `network_allow` is specified, Cloche creates\n   212→   a custom Docker network restricting egress to allowlisted domains via DNS proxy.\n   213→3. **Environment** — Configured in Dockerfile/image. Cloche does not inject env vars.\n   214→\n   215→## Capture System\n   216→\n   217→Each step execution is captured for later inspection and replay.\n   218→\n   219→### What Gets Captured\n   220→\n   221→- Step config (prompt, type, container settings)\n   222→- Input state (git ref of what was provided to the step)\n   223→- Output state (git ref of what the step produced)\n   224→- Result reported (which result name)\n   225→- Stdout/stderr logs\n   226→- Timing metadata\n   227→\n   228→### Storage\n   229→\n   230→Metadata in the store (SQLite initially). Git refs serve as pointers to actual file\n   231→states — no duplication of file content.\n   232→\n   233→## MVP Scope (v0.1)\n   234→\n   235→### In Scope\n   236→\n   237→- `cloche` CLI: `run`, `status`, `logs`, `stop`\n   238→- `cloched` daemon: container lifecycle, status collection, gRPC API, SQLite store\n   239→- `cloche-agent`: DSL parser, graph engine, agent/script execution, status reporting\n   240→- Workflow DSL: steps, results, wiring, `done`/`abort` terminals, `file()` references\n   241→- Container model: Docker, copy-in project files, git push for extraction, network allowlist\n   242→- Agent adapters: Generic (run a command) + Claude Code\n   243→- Capture system: Record step inputs/outputs/results\n   244→\n   245→### Post-MVP\n   246→\n   247→- Self-evolution: failure pattern analysis, automatic step injection into workflows\n   248→- Replay system: partial/full/dry replay of captured runs\n   249→- Auto-split commits into stacked branches\n   250→- Additional agent adapters\n   251→- Alternative storage backends (Postgres, DynamoDB)\n   252→- Alternative container runtimes (Podman, Firecracker)\n   253→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01R1LysqkAqfWYkfo6yeS54x","session_id":"a96b6437-5695-409b-8a85-fe8db249ea12","uuid":"ea71c6a3-9119-4b1f-af45-a733480918eb","timestamp":"2026-03-18T18:19:25.299Z"}
